      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, i'm working on this embedded C++ project for an automotive sensor module and we're hitting a wall. The system has about 512MB of RAM, but after about 4-6 hours of continuous operation, the heap just completely exhausts and the system crashes. It's not a massive spike, just a very slow, steady climb in usage. \n\nHere's a simplified snippet of the main loop where we handle the sensor data buffer:\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_sensor_data() {\n    uint8_t* buffer = new uint8_t[DATA_PACKET_SIZE];\n    \n    if (read_sensor(buffer) == SUCCESS) {\n        analyze_packet(buffer);\n    }\n    \n    // I thought I was handling it here\n    // delete[] buffer; \n}\n\nwhile (system_running) {\n    process_sensor_data();\n    sleep_ms(10);\n}\n```\n\nI checked the `analyze_packet` function and it doesn't seem to be taking ownership of the pointer. How can i systematically track down where this leak is happening? Normal Valgrind isn't really an option on this hardware.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Your snippet shows a heap entirely destroyed if `delete[] buffer` is missing, causing a 512 MB RAM leak after a few hours. Look for `analyze_packet` or other async callbacks that might be retaining `buffer` memory via smaller objects or re-allocating inside. Run Valgrind in headless or debug mode: `valgrind --leak-check=full --error-exitcode=1 ./app` over a live binary exec if supported, or add a simple counter in every allocation path to track growth. Once found, ensure you delete or move the memory ownership back to the caller, or switch to a static buffer pool.",
